[src:al-buckenberger/1889-columbus-solons-season] The **1889 Columbus Solons** baseball team finished with a 60–78 record, sixth place in the American Association during their debut season.
[src:al-buckenberger/1889-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1889 throughout the world.
[src:al-buckenberger/1889-in-baseball] New York defeated Brooklyn, six games to three.
[src:al-buckenberger/1890-columbus-solons-season] The **1890 Columbus Solons season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:al-buckenberger/1890-columbus-solons-season] The team finished with a 79–55 record, second place in the American Association.
[src:al-buckenberger/1890-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1890 throughout the world.
[src:al-buckenberger/1890-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:al-buckenberger/1892-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1892 throughout the world.
[src:al-buckenberger/1892-in-baseball] The National League played a split season schedule, with the teams that had the best record in each half of the season meeting in a postseason best-of-nine series, known at the time as the "World's Championship Series".
[src:al-buckenberger/1892-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1892 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was the 11th season of the Pittsburgh Pirates franchise; their sixth in the National League.
[src:al-buckenberger/1892-pittsburgh-pirates-season] In a split season schedule, the Pirates finished sixth in the first half of the season and fourth in the second half.
[src:al-buckenberger/1892-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Overall, the team had a record of 80–73, sixth-best in the 12-team National League.
[src:al-buckenberger/1893-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1893 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was the 12th season of the Pittsburgh Pirates franchise; their seventh season in the National League.
[src:al-buckenberger/1893-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates finished second in the National League with a record of 81 wins and 48 losses.
[src:al-buckenberger/al-buckenberger] Buckenberger was born in Detroit, Michigan, and began his career as an infielder, and then manager for minor league teams in the Midwest.
[src:al-buckenberger/al-buckenberger] In 1889 he became manager of the *Columbus Solons* of the American Association for two seasons.
[src:al-buckenberger/al-buckenberger] After a year at the minor league Sioux City, Iowa based Sioux City Cornhuskers he joined the National League *Pittsburgh Pirates* from 1892 to 1894, and then the *St.
[src:al-buckenberger/al-buckenberger] He managed the *Toronto Maple Leafs*, and the *Syracuse Stars* of the Eastern League for a year each, taking Syracuse to a first place finish in 1897.
[src:al-buckenberger/al-buckenberger] He then managed the Eastern League *Rochester Bronchos* from 1899 to 1901, finishing first-second-first.
[src:al-buckenberger/al-buckenberger] Following this he rejoined the National League as manager of the *Boston Beaneaters* from 1902 to 1904.
[src:al-buckenberger/al-buckenberger] He returned to Rochester between 1905 and 1908.
[src:al-buckenberger/al-buckenberger] Al Buckenberger also served as club president at Pittsburgh.
[src:al-buckenberger/al-buckenberger] His biggest successes were finishing second in the American Association in 1890 and finishing second in the National League at Pittsburgh in 1893.
[src:al-buckenberger/al-buckenberger] After his major league days he was part of a group, together with Francis Richter, editor of Sporting Life, and fellow manager Billy Barnie that tried and failed to resurrect the American Association.
[src:al-buckenberger/al-buckenberger] Buckenberger died at age 56 in Syracuse, New York.
